  "slug": "panettone",
  "title": "Panettone",
  "subtitle": "The Milanese Christmas bread, rich with citrus and dried fruit",
  "excerpt": "A tall, domed Italian Christmas bread built on a rich enriched dough: candied orange peel, raisins, and real butter layered into a light, airy crumb by two slow fermentations. Requires a panettone mould and patience.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "Panettone is a Milanese enriched bread documented from at least the late nineteenth century, with probable earlier origins. The structure here follows the traditional two-dough method (first dough plus second dough with extended fermentation) documented in Italian baking literature of the early twentieth century. Public-domain Italian household cooking manuals from the 1900s-1920s describe the enriched sweet bread of Milan and confirm the dried fruit and candied peel combination.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Panettone is not a quick bake. The traditional method uses two separate doughs, each fermented over many hours, which gives the bread its open, stringy crumb and delicate flavour. Made at home, it surpasses most commercial versions in lightness. This recipe uses dried yeast with a "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "sponge",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "term": "sponge",
                  "termId": "cmpbczygw0000cgv4nzlckbt7"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " pre-ferment to approximate the long fermentation of a traditional madre starter. Allow 2 days from start to finish."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "infoPanel",
        "attrs": {
          "title": "Equipment note"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "A stand mixer is not optional here; the dough requires very long mixing to develop sufficient gluten, and the high butter content makes hand-kneading impractical. You also need a panettone mould (a paper or metal one, 17 to 20 cm diameter). Tall round tins can substitute; line them with baking paper extending 10 cm above the rim. Domestic ovens drift by 20°C or more; an oven thermometer is recommended."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Ingredients"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "First dough (evening before)"
          }
        ]
